body: @tejaschandramohan It depends on which dataset the model is trained on. For example, if the output range of MOS of the training dataset is [1-10], then the ouput range of the model will also be [1-10].

Yes. But what is the range for dbcnn in general? I am not re-training, I am performing inference. 
For dbcnn, you have CSIQ, TID2013 and LIVE Challenge. These datasets have MOS in different scale. It is not clear from the paper to what the output range for the model is.
Is it [1-10] then?

csiq：0-1，tid2013: 0-9，live challenge：0-100

So I have to run dbcnn.py with some changes in code where I pass only my dataset, rather than csiq, live etc. Is that correct? (I am looking to fine-tune this model by training it for my dataset).

Can you confirm if the pretrained weights are available or not? Because first you mention you have not released the pretrained weights (see above conversation) and you mention the pretrained weights for scnn is provided. Are these two one and the same?

@tejaschandramohan Yes, you need to modify the dbcnn.py to finetune the dbcnn on your dataset. The weights of DBCNN is composed of three parts: scnn, (pre-trained) vgg-16, final fc layer. We have released the pre-trained weights of SCNN, then you need to finetune the all three parts together on your dataset.

Your model is originally trained on Live and LiveC dataset. The range of the output is 0-100 in this case. Correct?

The demo.py file provides evaluation for other images based on the training knowledge obtained from the datasets you used while training. Is that correct?
On which dataset is your pytorch model trained on?
